# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: http3-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:http3-protocol/http] HTTP/3 uses similar semantics compared to earlier revisions of the protocol, including the same request methods, status codes, and message fields, but encodes them and maintains session state differently.
[src:http3-protocol/http] However, partially due to the protocol's adoption of QUIC, HTTP/3 has lower latency and loads more quickly in real-world usage when compared with previous versions: in some cases over four times faster than with HTTP/1.1 (which, for many websites, is the only HTTP version deployed).
[src:http3-protocol/http] As of September 2024, HTTP/3 is supported by more than 95% of major web browsers in use and 34% of the top 10 million websites.
[src:http3-protocol/http] It has been supported by Chromium (and derived projects including Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Samsung Internet, and Opera) since April 2020 and by Mozilla Firefox since May 2021.
[src:http3-protocol/http] HTTP/3 originates from an Internet Draft adopted by the QUIC working group.
[src:http3-protocol/http] The original proposal was named "HTTP/2 Semantics Using The QUIC Transport Protocol", and later renamed "Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) over QUIC".
[src:http3-protocol/http] On 28 October 2018 in a mailing list discussion, Mark Nottingham, Chair of the IETF HTTP and QUIC Working Groups, proposed renaming HTTP-over-QUIC to HTTP/3, to "clearly identify it as another binding of HTTP semantics to the wire protocol [...] so people understand its separation from QUIC".
[src:http3-protocol/http] Nottingham's proposal was accepted by fellow IETF members a few days later.
[src:http3-protocol/http] The HTTP working group was chartered to assist the QUIC working group during the design of HTTP/3, then assume responsibility for maintenance after publication.
[src:http3-protocol/http] Support for HTTP/3 was added to Chrome (Canary build) in September 2019 and then eventually reached stable builds, but was disabled by a feature flag.
[src:http3-protocol/http] It was enabled by default in April 2020.
[src:http3-protocol/http] Firefox added support for HTTP/3 in November 2019 through a feature flag and started enabling it by default in April 2021 in Firefox 88.
[src:http3-protocol/http] Experimental support for HTTP/3 was added to Safari Technology Preview on April 8, 2020 and was included with Safari 14 that ships with iOS 14 and macOS 11,.
[src:http3-protocol/http] Starting September 2024, HTTP/3 is supported for all users on Safari 16 or newer.
[src:http3-protocol/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF published HTTP/3 as a Proposed Standard in RFC 9114.
[src:http3-protocol/http] HTTP semantics are consistent across versions: the same request methods, status codes, and message fields are typically applicable to all versions.
[src:http3-protocol/http] The differences are in the mapping of these semantics to underlying transports.
[src:http3-protocol/http] Both HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 use TCP as their transport.
[src:http3-protocol/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC, a transport layer network protocol which uses user space congestion control over the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:http3-protocol/http] Because QUIC provides native multiplexing, lost packets only impact the streams where data has been lost.
[src:http3-protocol/http] The HTTPS DNS resource record as defined in RFC 9460 allows for connecting without first receiving the Alt-Svc header via previous HTTP versions, therefore removing the 1 RTT of handshaking of TCP.
[src:http3-protocol/http] There is client support for HTTPS resource records since Firefox 92, iOS 14, reported Safari 14 support, and Chromium supports it behind a flag.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC improves performance of connection-oriented web applications that previously relied on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It does this by establishing a number of multiplexed connections between two endpoints using User Datagram Protocol (UDP), and it is designed to obsolete TCP at the transport layer for many applications.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Although its name was initially proposed as an acronym for *Quick UDP Internet Connections*, in IETF's use of the word *QUIC* is not an acronym; it is simply the name of the protocol.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC works hand-in-hand with HTTP/3's multiplexed connections, allowing multiple streams of data to reach all the endpoints independently, and hence independent of packet losses involving other streams.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In contrast, HTTP/2, which is carried over TCP, can suffer head-of-line-blocking delays if multiple streams are multiplexed on a TCP connection and any of the TCP packets on that connection are delayed or lost.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC's secondary goals include reduced connection and transport latency, and bandwidth estimation in each direction to avoid congestion.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It also moves congestion control algorithms into the user space at both endpoints, rather than the kernel space, which is claimed to allow these algorithms to improve more rapidly.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Additionally, the protocol can be extended with forward error correction (FEC) to further improve performance when errors are expected.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It is designed with the intention of avoiding protocol ossification.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In June 2015, an Internet Draft of a specification for QUIC was submitted to the IETF for standardization.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] A QUIC working group was established in 2016.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In October 2018, the IETF's HTTP and QUIC Working Groups jointly decided to call the HTTP mapping over QUIC "HTTP/3" in advance of making it a worldwide standard.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In May 2021, the IETF standardized QUIC in RFC 9000, supported by RFC 8999, 9001 and 9002.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Transmission Control Protocol, or TCP, aims to provide an interface for sending streams of data between two endpoints.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Data is sent to the TCP system, which ensures it reaches the other end in the exact same form; if any discrepancies occur, the connection will signal an error condition.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] To do this, TCP breaks up the data into network packets and adds small amounts of data to each packet.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This additional data includes a sequence number that is used to detect packets that are lost or arrive out of order, and a checksum that allows the errors within packet data to be detected.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] When either problem occurs, TCP uses automatic repeat request (ARQ) to ask the sender to re-send the lost or damaged packet.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In most implementations, TCP will see any error on a connection as a blocking operation, stopping further transfers until the error is resolved or the connection is considered failed.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] If a single connection is being used to send multiple streams of data, as is the case in the HTTP/2 protocol, all of these streams are blocked although only one of them might have a problem.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] For instance, if a single error occurs while downloading a GIF image used for a favicon, the entire rest of the page will wait while that problem is resolved.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This phenomenon is known as head-of-line blocking.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] As the TCP system is designed to look like a "data pipe", or stream, it deliberately has little information regarding the data it transmits.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] If that data has additional requirements, like encryption using TLS, this must be set up by systems running on top of TCP, using TCP to communicate with similar software on the other end of the connection.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Each of these sorts of setup tasks requires its own handshake process.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This often requires several round-trips of requests and responses until the connection is established.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Due to the inherent latency of long-distance communications, this can add significant delay to the overall transmission.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] TCP has suffered from protocol ossification, due to its wire image being in cleartext and hence visible to and malleable by middleboxes.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] One measurement found that a third of paths across the Internet encounter at least one intermediary that modifies TCP metadata, and 6.5% of paths encounter harmful ossifying effects from intermediaries.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Extensions to TCP have been affected: the design of Multipath TCP (MPTCP) was constrained by middlebox behaviour, and the deployment of TCP Fast Open has been likewise hindered.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In the context of supporting encrypted HTTP traffic, QUIC serves a role similar to that of TCP, but with reduced latency during connection setup and more efficient loss recovery when multiple HTTP streams are multiplexed over a single connection.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It does this primarily through two changes that rely on the understanding of the behaviour of HTTP traffic.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The first change is to greatly reduce overhead during connection setup.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] As most HTTP connections will demand TLS, QUIC makes the exchange of setup keys and listing of supported protocols part of the initial handshake process.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] When a client opens a connection, the response packet includes the data needed for future packets to use encryption.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This eliminates the need to set up an unencrypted *pipe* and then negotiate the security protocol as separate steps.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Other protocols can be serviced in the same way, combining multiple steps into a single request–response pair.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This data can then be used both for following requests in the initial setup and future requests that would otherwise be negotiated as separate connections.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The second change is to use UDP rather than TCP as its basis, which does not include loss recovery.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Instead, each QUIC stream is separately flow-controlled, and lost data is retransmitted at the level of QUIC, not UDP.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This means that if an error occurs in one stream, like the favicon example above, the protocol stack can continue servicing other streams independently.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This can be very useful in improving performance on error-prone links, as in most cases considerable additional data may be received before TCP notices a packet is missing or broken, and all of this data is blocked or even flushed while the error is corrected.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In QUIC, this data is free to be processed while the single multiplexed stream is repaired.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC includes a number of other changes that improve overall latency and throughput.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] For instance, the packets are encrypted individually, so that they do not result in the encrypted data waiting for partial packets.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This is not generally possible under TCP, where the encryption records are in a bytestream and the protocol stack is unaware of higher-layer boundaries within this stream.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] These can be negotiated by the layers running on top, but QUIC aims to do all of this in a single handshake process.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Another goal of the QUIC system was to improve performance during network-switching events, like what happens when a user of a mobile device moves from a local Wi-Fi hotspot to a mobile network.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] When this occurs on TCP, a lengthy process starts where every existing connection times out one-by-one and is then re-established on demand.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] To solve this problem, QUIC includes a connection identifier to uniquely identify the connection to the server regardless of source.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This allows the connection to be re-established simply by sending a packet, which always contains this ID, as the original connection ID will still be valid even if the user's IP address changes.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC can be implemented in the application space, as opposed to being in the operating system kernel.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This generally invokes additional overhead due to context switches as data is moved between applications.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] However, in the case of QUIC, the protocol stack is intended to be used by a single application, with each application using QUIC having its own connections hosted on UDP.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Ultimately the difference could be very small because much of the overall HTTP/2 stack is already in the applications (or their libraries, more commonly).
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Placing the remaining parts in those libraries, essentially the error correction, has little effect on the HTTP/2 stack's size or overall complexity.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This organization allows future changes to be made more easily as it does not require changes to the kernel for updates.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] One of QUIC's longer-term goals is to add new systems for forward error correction (FEC) and improved congestion control.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] One concern about the move from TCP to UDP is that TCP is widely adopted and many of the "middleboxes" in the Internet infrastructure are tuned for TCP and rate-limit or even block UDP.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Google carried out a number of exploratory experiments to characterize this and found that only a small number of connections were blocked in this manner.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] This led to the use of a system for rapid fallback to TCP; Chromium's network stack starts both a QUIC and a conventional TCP connection at the same time, which allows it to fall back with negligible latency.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC has been specifically designed to be deployable and evolvable and to have anti-ossification properties; it is the first IETF transport protocol to deliberately minimise its wire image for these ends.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Beyond encrypted headers, it is 'greased' and it has protocol invariants explicitly specified.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The security layer of QUIC is based on TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Earlier insecure protocols such as TLS 1.0 are not allowed in a QUIC stack.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The protocol originally developed by Google, known as gQUIC, was first deployed around 2012 and later brought to the IETF.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] However, the version of QUIC standardized by the IETF is significantly different from the earlier Google implementation.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Google's QUIC was initially designed as a general-purpose web protocol and was deployed mainly to support HTTP and HTTPS in Chromium, using its own encryption and transport mechanisms.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In contrast, the IETF QUIC protocol has been redeveloped as a general-purpose transport protocol that uses standard TLS 1.3 for its cryptographic handshake and incorporates a modular packet and connection design intended for broader interoperability.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Chromium developers have continued to follow the progress of IETF QUIC standardization and have worked to adopt and comply with the evolving Internet standards for QUIC within Chromium.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The transition to IETF QUIC in Chrome began progressing publicly around 2020.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] QUIC was developed with HTTP in mind, and HTTP/3 was its first application.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] DNS-over-QUIC is an application of QUIC to name resolution, providing security for data transferred between resolvers similar to DNS-over-TLS.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The IETF is developing applications of QUIC for secure network tunnelling and streaming media delivery.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] XMPP has experimentally been adapted to use QUIC.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Another application is SMB over QUIC, which, according to Microsoft, can offer an "SMB VPN" without affecting the user experience.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] SMB clients use TCP by default and will attempt QUIC if the TCP attempt fails or if intentionally requiring QUIC.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The QUIC code was experimentally developed in Google Chrome starting in 2012, and was announced as part of Chromium version 29 (released on August 20, 2013).
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It is currently enabled by default in Chromium and Chrome.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Apple added experimental support in the WebKit engine through the Safari Technology Preview 104 in April 2020.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Official support was added in Safari 14, included in macOS Big Sur and iOS 14, but the feature needed to be turned on manually.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] It was later enabled by default in Safari 16.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The cronet library for QUIC and other protocols is available to Android applications as a module loadable via Google Play Services.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] cURL 7.66, released 11 September 2019, supports HTTP/3 (and thus QUIC).
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In October 2020, Facebook announced that it has successfully migrated its apps, including Instagram, and server infrastructure to QUIC, with already 75% of its Internet traffic using QUIC.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] All mobile apps from Google support QUIC, including YouTube and Gmail.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] As of 2017, there are several actively maintained implementations.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Google servers support QUIC and Google has published a prototype server.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Akamai Technologies has supported QUIC since July 2016.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] A Go implementation called quic-go is also available, and powers experimental QUIC support in the Caddy server.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] On July 11, 2017, LiteSpeed Technologies officially began supporting QUIC in their load balancer (WebADC) and LiteSpeed Web Server products.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] As of October 2019, 88.6% of QUIC websites used LiteSpeed and 10.8% used Nginx.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Although at first only Google servers supported HTTP-over-QUIC connections, Facebook also launched the technology in 2018, and Cloudflare has been offering QUIC support on a beta basis since 2018.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The HAProxy load balancer added experimental support for QUIC in March 2022 and declared it production-ready in March 2023.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] As of April 2023, 8.9% of all websites use QUIC, up from 5% in March 2021.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Microsoft Windows Server 2022 supports both HTTP/3 and SMB over QUIC protocols via MsQuic.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] The Application Delivery Controller of Citrix (Citrix ADC, NetScaler) can function as a QUIC proxy since version 13.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] In addition, there are several stale community projects: libquic was created by extracting the Chromium implementation of QUIC and modifying it to minimize dependency requirements, and goquic provides Go bindings of libquic.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] Finally, quic-reverse-proxy is a Docker image that acts as a reverse proxy server, translating QUIC requests into plain HTTP that can be understood by the origin server.
[src:http3-protocol/quic] .NET 5 introduces experimental support for QUIC using the MsQuic library.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The QUIC transport protocol has several features that are desirable in a transport for HTTP, such as stream multiplexing, per-stream flow control, and low-latency connection establishment.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This document describes a mapping of HTTP semantics over QUIC.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This document is a product of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] It represents the consensus of the IETF community.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] It has received public review and has been approved for publication by the Internet Engineering Steering Group (IESG).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Copyright (c) 2022 IETF Trust and the persons identified as the document authors.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This document is subject to BCP 78 and the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions Relating to IETF Documents (https://trustee.ietf.org/license-info) in effect on the date of publication of this document.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Please review these documents carefully, as they describe your rights and restrictions with respect to this document.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP semantics ([HTTP]) are used for a broad range of services on the Internet.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] These semantics have most commonly been used with HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/1.1 has been used over a variety of transport and session layers, while HTTP/2 has been used primarily with TLS over TCP.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/1.1 ([HTTP/1.1]) uses whitespace-delimited text fields to convey HTTP messages.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Because HTTP/1.1 does not include a multiplexing layer, multiple TCP connections are often used to service requests in parallel.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/2 ([HTTP/2]) introduced a binary framing and multiplexing layer to improve latency without modifying the transport layer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The QUIC transport protocol incorporates stream multiplexing and per-stream flow control, similar to that provided by the HTTP/2 framing layer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] By providing reliability at the stream level and congestion control across the entire connection, QUIC has the capability to improve the performance of HTTP compared to a TCP mapping.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This document defines HTTP/3: a mapping of HTTP semantics over the QUIC transport protocol, drawing heavily on the design of HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 relies on QUIC to provide confidentiality and integrity protection of data; peer authentication; and reliable, in-order, per-stream delivery.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] While delegating stream lifetime and flow-control issues to QUIC, a binary framing similar to the HTTP/2 framing is used on each stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Once a client knows that an HTTP/3 server exists at a certain endpoint, it opens a QUIC connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] QUIC provides protocol negotiation, stream-based multiplexing, and flow control.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Within each stream, the basic unit of HTTP/3 communication is a frame (Section 7.2).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Each frame type serves a different purpose.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For example, HEADERS and DATA frames form the basis of HTTP requests and responses (Section 4.1).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Multiplexing of requests is performed using the QUIC stream abstraction, which is described in Section 2 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Each request-response pair consumes a single QUIC stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Server push is an interaction mode introduced in HTTP/2 ([HTTP/2]) that permits a server to push a request-response exchange to a client in anticipation of the client making the indicated request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This trades off network usage against a potential latency gain.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] As in HTTP/2, request and response fields are compressed for transmission.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Because HPACK ([HPACK]) relies on in-order transmission of compressed field sections (a guarantee not provided by QUIC), HTTP/3 replaces HPACK with QPACK ([QPACK]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The endpoint that initiates an HTTP/3 connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Protocol elements called "frames" exist in both this document and [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Where frames from [QUIC-TRANSPORT] are referenced, the frame name will be prefaced with "QUIC".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For example, "QUIC CONNECTION_CLOSE frames".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The endpoint that accepts an HTTP/3 connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A bidirectional or unidirectional bytestream provided by the QUIC transport.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The "https" scheme associates authority with possession of a certificate that the client considers to be trustworthy for the host identified by the authority component of the URI.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Upon receiving a server certificate in the TLS handshake, the client MUST verify that the certificate is an acceptable match for the URI's origin server using the process described in Section 4.3.4 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Although HTTP is independent of the transport protocol, the "http" scheme associates authority with the ability to receive TCP connections on the indicated port of whatever host is identified within the authority component.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Because HTTP/3 does not use TCP, HTTP/3 cannot be used for direct access to the authoritative server for a resource identified by an "http" URI.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Prior to making requests for an origin whose scheme is not "https", the client MUST ensure the server is willing to serve that scheme.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For origins whose scheme is "http", an experimental method to accomplish this is described in [RFC8164].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 relies on QUIC version 1 as the underlying transport.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] QUIC version 1 uses TLS version 1.3 or greater as its handshake protocol.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 clients MUST support a mechanism to indicate the target host to the server during the TLS handshake.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] QUIC connections are established as described in [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] During connection establishment, HTTP/3 support is indicated by selecting the ALPN token "h3" in the TLS handshake.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] While connection-level options pertaining to the core QUIC protocol are set in the initial crypto handshake, settings specific to HTTP/3 are conveyed in the SETTINGS frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 connections are persistent across multiple requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Once a connection to a server endpoint exists, this connection MAY be reused for requests with multiple different URI authority components.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] To use an existing connection for a new origin, clients MUST validate the certificate presented by the server for the new origin server using the process described in Section 4.3.4 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the certificate is not acceptable with regard to the new origin for any reason, the connection MUST NOT be reused and a new connection SHOULD be established for the new origin.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the reason the certificate cannot be verified might apply to other origins already associated with the connection, the client SHOULD revalidate the server certificate for those origins.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients SHOULD NOT open more than one HTTP/3 connection to a given IP address and UDP port, where the IP address and port might be derived from a URI, a selected alternative service ([ALTSVC]), a configured proxy, or name resolution of any of these.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Servers are encouraged to maintain open HTTP/3 connections for as long as possible but are permitted to terminate idle connections if necessary.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A client sends an HTTP request on a request stream, which is a client-initiated bidirectional QUIC stream; see Section 6.1.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A client MUST send only a single request on a given stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server sends zero or more interim HTTP responses on the same stream as the request, followed by a single final HTTP response, as detailed below.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pushed responses are sent on a server-initiated unidirectional QUIC stream; see Section 6.2.2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server sends zero or more interim HTTP responses, followed by a single final HTTP response, in the same manner as a standard response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Receipt of an invalid sequence of frames MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_FRAME_UNEXPECTED.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] In particular, a DATA frame before any HEADERS frame, or a HEADERS or DATA frame after the trailing HEADERS frame, is considered invalid.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server MAY send one or more PUSH_PROMISE frames before, after, or interleaved with the frames of a response message.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] These PUSH_PROMISE frames are not part of the response; see Section 4.6 for more details.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The HEADERS and PUSH_PROMISE frames might reference updates to the QPACK dynamic table.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] While these updates are not directly part of the message exchange, they must be received and processed before the message can be consumed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A response MAY consist of multiple messages when and only when one or more interim responses (1xx; see Section 15.2 of [HTTP]) precede a final response to the same request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] An HTTP request/response exchange fully consumes a client-initiated bidirectional QUIC stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] After sending a request, a client MUST close the stream for sending.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Unless using the CONNECT method (see Section 4.4), clients MUST NOT make stream closure dependent on receiving a response to their request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] After sending a final response, the server MUST close the stream for sending.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When a stream is closed, this indicates the end of the final HTTP message.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Because some messages are large or unbounded, endpoints SHOULD begin processing partial HTTP messages once enough of the message has been received to make progress.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server can send a complete response prior to the client sending an entire request if the response does not depend on any portion of the request that has not been sent and received.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When the server does not need to receive the remainder of the request, it MAY abort reading the request stream, send a complete response, and cleanly close the sending part of the stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The error code H3_NO_ERROR SHOULD be used when requesting that the client stop sending on the request stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients MUST NOT discard complete responses as a result of having their request terminated abruptly, though clients can always discard responses at their discretion for other reasons.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Once a request stream has been opened, the request MAY be cancelled by either endpoint.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients cancel requests if the response is no longer of interest; servers cancel requests if they are unable to or choose not to respond.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Implementations SHOULD cancel requests by abruptly terminating any directions of a stream that are still open.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When the server cancels a request without performing any application processing, the request is considered "rejected".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The server SHOULD abort its response stream with the error code H3_REQUEST_REJECTED.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] In this context, "processed" means that some data from the stream was passed to some higher layer of software that might have taken some action as a result.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Servers MUST NOT use the H3_REQUEST_REJECTED error code for requests that were partially or fully processed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Client SHOULD use the error code H3_REQUEST_CANCELLED to cancel requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Upon receipt of this error code, a server MAY abruptly terminate the response using the error code H3_REQUEST_REJECTED if no processing was performed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If a stream is cancelled after receiving a complete response, the client MAY ignore the cancellation and use the response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] However, if a stream is cancelled after receiving a partial response, the response SHOULD NOT be used.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A request or response that is defined as having content when it contains a Content-Length header field (Section 8.6 of [HTTP]) is malformed if the value of the Content-Length header field does not equal the sum of the DATA frame lengths received.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Intermediaries that process HTTP requests or responses (i.e., any intermediary not acting as a tunnel) MUST NOT forward a malformed request or response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For malformed requests, a server MAY send an HTTP response indicating the error prior to closing or resetting the stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients MUST NOT accept a malformed response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP messages carry metadata as a series of key-value pairs called "HTTP fields"; see Sections 6.3 and 6.5 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For a listing of registered HTTP fields, see the "Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) Field Name Registry" maintained at <https://www.iana.org/assignments/http-fields/>.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Field names are strings containing a subset of ASCII characters.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Properties of HTTP field names and values are discussed in more detail in Section 5.1 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Characters in field names MUST be converted to lowercase prior to their encoding.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 does not use the Connection header field to indicate connection-specific fields; in this protocol, connection-specific metadata is conveyed by other means.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] [QPACK] describes a variation of HPACK that gives an encoder some control over how much head-of-line blocking can be caused by compression.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This allows an encoder to balance compression efficiency with latency.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] To allow for better compression efficiency, the Cookie header field ([COOKIES]) MAY be split into separate field lines, each with one or more cookie-pairs, before compression.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] An HTTP/3 implementation MAY impose a limit on the maximum size of the message header it will accept on an individual HTTP message.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server that receives a larger header section than it is willing to handle can send an HTTP 431 (Request Header Fields Too Large) status code ([RFC6585]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A client can discard responses that it cannot process.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If an implementation wishes to advise its peer of this limit, it can be conveyed as a number of bytes in the SETTINGS_MAX_FIELD_SECTION_SIZE parameter.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] An implementation that has received this parameter SHOULD NOT send an HTTP message header that exceeds the indicated size, as the peer will likely refuse to process it.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] However, an HTTP message can traverse one or more intermediaries before reaching the origin server; see Section 3.7 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Like HTTP/2, HTTP/3 employs a series of pseudo-header fields, where the field name begins with the `:` character (ASCII 0x3a).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pseudo-header fields are not HTTP fields.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Endpoints MUST NOT generate pseudo-header fields other than those defined in this document.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pseudo-header fields are only valid in the context in which they are defined.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pseudo-header fields defined for requests MUST NOT appear in responses; pseudo-header fields defined for responses MUST NOT appear in requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pseudo-header fields MUST NOT appear in trailer sections.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] All pseudo-header fields MUST appear in the header section before regular header fields.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The :scheme pseudo-header is not restricted to URIs with scheme "http" and "https".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Contains the authority portion of the target URI (Section 3.2 of [URI]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] To ensure that the HTTP/1.1 request line can be reproduced accurately, this pseudo-header field MUST be omitted when translating from an HTTP/1.1 request that has a request target in a method-specific form; see Section 7.1 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients that generate HTTP/3 requests directly SHOULD use the :authority pseudo-header field instead of the Host header field.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This pseudo-header field MUST NOT be empty for "http" or "https" URIs; "http" or "https" URIs that do not contain a path component MUST include a value of `/` (ASCII 0x2f).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the :scheme pseudo-header field identifies a scheme that has a mandatory authority component (including "http" and "https"), the request MUST contain either an :authority pseudo-header field or a Host header field.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If these fields are present, they MUST NOT be empty.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If both fields are present, they MUST contain the same value.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 does not define a way to carry the version identifier that is included in the HTTP/1.1 request line.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] For responses, a single ":status" pseudo-header field is defined that carries the HTTP status code; see Section 15 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] HTTP/3 does not define a way to carry the version or reason phrase that is included in an HTTP/1.1 status line.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The CONNECT method requests that the recipient establish a tunnel to the destination origin server identified by the request-target; see Section 9.3.6 of [HTTP].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] In HTTP/1.x, CONNECT is used to convert an entire HTTP connection into a tunnel to a remote host.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The request stream remains open at the end of the request to carry the data to be transferred.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A proxy that supports CONNECT establishes a TCP connection ([RFC0793]) to the server identified in the :authority pseudo-header field.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] All DATA frames on the stream correspond to data sent or received on the TCP connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The payload of any DATA frame sent by the client is transmitted by the proxy to the TCP server; data received from the TCP server is packaged into DATA frames by the proxy.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Once the CONNECT method has completed, only DATA frames are permitted to be sent on the stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Extension frames MAY be used if specifically permitted by the definition of the extension.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The TCP connection can be closed by either peer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When the client ends the request stream (that is, the receive stream at the proxy enters the "Data Recvd" state), the proxy will set the FIN bit on its connection to the TCP server.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When the proxy receives a packet with the FIN bit set, it will close the send stream that it sends to the client.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A TCP connection error is signaled by abruptly terminating the stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Correspondingly, if a proxy detects an error with the stream or the QUIC connection, it MUST close the TCP connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the proxy detects that the client has reset the stream or aborted reading from the stream, it MUST close the TCP connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the stream is reset or reading is aborted by the client, a proxy SHOULD perform the same operation on the other direction in order to ensure that both directions of the stream are cancelled.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Server push is an interaction mode that permits a server to push a request-response exchange to a client in anticipation of the client making the indicated request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Each server push is assigned a unique push ID by the server.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The push ID space begins at zero and ends at a maximum value set by the MAX_PUSH_ID frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] In particular, a server is not able to push until after the client sends a MAX_PUSH_ID frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A client sends MAX_PUSH_ID frames to control the number of pushes that a server can promise.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] A server SHOULD use push IDs sequentially, beginning from zero.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The push ID is used in one or more PUSH_PROMISE frames that carry the control data and header fields of the request message.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] These frames are sent on the request stream that generated the push.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] This allows the server push to be associated with a client request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The push ID is then included with the push stream that ultimately fulfills those promises.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Finally, the push ID can be used in CANCEL_PUSH frames; see Section 7.2.3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients use this frame to indicate they do not wish to receive a promised resource.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The server MUST include a value in the :authority pseudo-header field for which the server is authoritative.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] If the client has not yet validated the connection for the origin indicated by the pushed request, it MUST perform the same verification process it would do before sending a request for that origin on the connection; see Section 3.3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Clients SHOULD send a CANCEL_PUSH frame upon receipt of a PUSH_PROMISE frame carrying a request that is not cacheable, is not known to be safe, that indicates the presence of request content, or for which it does not consider the server authoritative.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Each pushed response is associated with one or more client requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The push is associated with the request stream on which the PUSH_PROMISE frame was received.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The same server push can be associated with additional client requests using a PUSH_PROMISE frame with the same push ID on multiple request streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Ordering of a PUSH_PROMISE frame in relation to certain parts of the response is important.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The server SHOULD send PUSH_PROMISE frames prior to sending HEADERS or DATA frames that reference the promised responses.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Due to reordering, push stream data can arrive before the corresponding PUSH_PROMISE frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] When a client receives a new push stream with an as-yet-unknown push ID, both the associated client request and the pushed request header fields are unknown.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The client can buffer the stream data in expectation of the matching PUSH_PROMISE.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] The client can use stream flow control (Section 4.1 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT]) to limit the amount of data a server may commit to the pushed stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Push stream data can also arrive after a client has cancelled a push.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] In this case, the client can abort reading the stream with an error code of H3_REQUEST_CANCELLED.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pushed responses that are cacheable (see Section 3 of [HTTP-CACHING]) can be stored by the client, if it implements an HTTP cache.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p01] Pushed responses that are not cacheable MUST NOT be stored by any HTTP cache.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Once established, an HTTP/3 connection can be used for many requests and responses over time until the connection is closed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each QUIC endpoint declares an idle timeout during the handshake.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the QUIC connection remains idle (no packets received) for longer than this duration, the peer will assume that the connection has been closed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HTTP clients are expected to request that the transport keep connections open while there are responses outstanding for requests or server pushes, as described in Section 10.1.2 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the client is not expecting a response from the server, allowing an idle connection to time out is preferred over expending effort maintaining a connection that might not be needed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A gateway MAY maintain connections in anticipation of need rather than incur the latency cost of connection establishment to servers.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Even when a connection is not idle, either endpoint can decide to stop using the connection and initiate a graceful connection close.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Endpoints initiate the graceful shutdown of an HTTP/3 connection by sending a GOAWAY frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The GOAWAY frame contains an identifier that indicates to the receiver the range of requests or pushes that were or might be processed in this connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The server sends a client-initiated bidirectional stream ID; the client sends a push ID.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Requests or pushes with the indicated identifier or greater are rejected (Section 4.1.1) by the sender of the GOAWAY.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The information in the GOAWAY frame enables a client and server to agree on which requests or pushes were accepted prior to the shutdown of the HTTP/3 connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Upon sending a GOAWAY frame, the endpoint SHOULD explicitly cancel (see Sections 4.1.1 and 7.2.3) any requests or pushes that have identifiers greater than or equal to the one indicated, in order to clean up transport state for the affected streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Endpoints MUST NOT initiate new requests or promise new pushes on the connection after receipt of a GOAWAY frame from the peer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Servers SHOULD send a GOAWAY frame when the closing of a connection is known in advance, even if the advance notice is small, so that the remote peer can know whether or not a request has been partially processed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] An endpoint MAY send multiple GOAWAY frames indicating different identifiers, but the identifier in each frame MUST NOT be greater than the identifier in any previous frame, since clients might already have retried unprocessed requests on another HTTP connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] An endpoint that is attempting to gracefully shut down a connection can send a GOAWAY frame with a value set to the maximum possible value (262-4 for servers, 262-1 for clients).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This ensures that the peer stops creating new requests or pushes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] After allowing time for any in-flight requests or pushes to arrive, the endpoint can send another GOAWAY frame indicating which requests or pushes it might accept before the end of the connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A client has more flexibility in the value it chooses for the Push ID field in a GOAWAY that it sends.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A value of 262-1 indicates that the server can continue fulfilling pushes that have already been promised.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A smaller value indicates the client will reject pushes with push IDs greater than or equal to this value.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Even when a GOAWAY indicates that a given request or push will not be processed or accepted upon receipt, the underlying transport resources still exist.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Once all accepted requests and pushes have been processed, the endpoint can permit the connection to become idle, or it MAY initiate an immediate closure of the connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] An HTTP/3 implementation can immediately close the QUIC connection at any time.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This results in sending a QUIC CONNECTION_CLOSE frame to the peer indicating that the application layer has terminated the connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The application error code in this frame indicates to the peer why the connection is being closed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Before closing the connection, a GOAWAY frame MAY be sent to allow the client to retry some requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] For various reasons, the QUIC transport could indicate to the application layer that the connection has terminated.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A QUIC stream provides reliable in-order delivery of bytes, but makes no guarantees about order of delivery with regard to bytes on other streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] In version 1 of QUIC, the stream data containing HTTP frames is carried by QUIC STREAM frames, but this framing is invisible to the HTTP framing layer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The transport layer buffers and orders received stream data, exposing a reliable byte stream to the application.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] QUIC streams can be either unidirectional, carrying data only from initiator to receiver, or bidirectional, carrying data in both directions.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Streams can be initiated by either the client or the server.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When HTTP fields and data are sent over QUIC, the QUIC layer handles most of the stream management.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] All client-initiated bidirectional streams are used for HTTP requests and responses.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A bidirectional stream ensures that the response can be readily correlated with the request.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This means that the client's first request occurs on QUIC stream 0, with subsequent requests on streams 4, 8, and so on.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] In order to permit these streams to open, an HTTP/3 server SHOULD configure non-zero minimum values for the number of permitted streams and the initial stream flow-control window.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HTTP/3 does not use server-initiated bidirectional streams, though an extension could define a use for these streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Unidirectional streams, in either direction, are used for a range of purposes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The purpose is indicated by a stream type, which is sent as a variable-length integer at the start of the stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Two stream types are defined in this document: control streams (Section 6.2.1) and push streams (Section 6.2.2). [QPACK] defines two additional stream types.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Other stream types can be defined by extensions to HTTP/3; see Section 9 for more details.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The performance of HTTP/3 connections in the early phase of their lifetime is sensitive to the creation and exchange of data on unidirectional streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Endpoints that excessively restrict the number of streams or the flow-control window of these streams will increase the chance that the remote peer reaches the limit early and becomes blocked.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each endpoint needs to create at least one unidirectional stream for the HTTP control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] QPACK requires two additional unidirectional streams, and other extensions might require further streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Therefore, the transport parameters sent by both clients and servers MUST allow the peer to create at least three unidirectional streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Note that an endpoint is not required to grant additional credits to create more unidirectional streams if its peer consumes all the initial credits before creating the critical unidirectional streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the stream header indicates a stream type that is not supported by the recipient, the remainder of the stream cannot be consumed as the semantics are unknown.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Recipients of unknown stream types MUST either abort reading of the stream or discard incoming data without further processing.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If reading is aborted, the recipient SHOULD use the H3_STREAM_CREATION_ERROR error code or a reserved error code (Section 8.1).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Implementations MAY send stream types before knowing whether the peer supports them.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A sender can close or reset a unidirectional stream unless otherwise specified.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A control stream is indicated by a stream type of 0x00.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each side MUST initiate a single control stream at the beginning of the connection and send its SETTINGS frame as the first frame on this stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the first frame of the control stream is any other frame type, this MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_MISSING_SETTINGS.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Only one control stream per peer is permitted; receipt of a second stream claiming to be a control stream MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_STREAM_CREATION_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The sender MUST NOT close the control stream, and the receiver MUST NOT request that the sender close the control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If either control stream is closed at any point, this MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_CLOSED_CRITICAL_STREAM.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A pair of unidirectional streams is used rather than a single bidirectional stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This allows either peer to send data as soon as it is able.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Server push is an optional feature introduced in HTTP/2 that allows a server to initiate a response before a request has been made.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A push stream is indicated by a stream type of 0x01, followed by the push ID of the promise that it fulfills, encoded as a variable-length integer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The remaining data on this stream consists of HTTP/3 frames, as defined in Section 7.2, and fulfills a promised server push by zero or more interim HTTP responses followed by a single final HTTP response, as defined in Section 4.1.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each push ID MUST only be used once in a push stream header.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Stream types of the format `0x1f * N + 0x21` for non-negative integer values of `N` are reserved to exercise the requirement that unknown types be ignored.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] These streams have no semantics, and they can be sent when application-layer padding is desired.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] They MAY also be sent on connections where no data is currently being transferred.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The payload and length of the stream are selected in any manner the sending implementation chooses.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When sending a reserved stream type, the implementation MAY either terminate the stream cleanly or reset it.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HTTP frames are carried on QUIC streams, as described in Section 6.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HTTP/3 defines three stream types: control stream, request stream, and push stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This section describes HTTP/3 frame formats and their permitted stream types; see Table 1 for an overview.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The SETTINGS frame can only occur as the first frame of a Control stream; this is indicated in Table 1 with a (1).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each frame's payload MUST contain exactly the fields identified in its description.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A frame payload that contains additional bytes after the identified fields or a frame payload that terminates before the end of the identified fields MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_FRAME_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When a stream terminates cleanly, if the last frame on the stream was truncated, this MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_FRAME_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] DATA frames MUST be associated with an HTTP request or response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The HEADERS frame (type=0x01) is used to carry an HTTP field section that is encoded using QPACK.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HEADERS frames can only be sent on request streams or push streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The CANCEL_PUSH frame (type=0x03) is used to request cancellation of a server push prior to the push stream being received.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When a client sends a CANCEL_PUSH frame, it is indicating that it does not wish to receive the promised resource.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The server SHOULD abort sending the resource, but the mechanism to do so depends on the state of the corresponding push stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the server has not yet created a push stream, it does not create one.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the push stream is open, the server SHOULD abruptly terminate that stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server sends a CANCEL_PUSH frame to indicate that it will not be fulfilling a promise that was previously sent.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The client cannot expect the corresponding promise to be fulfilled, unless it has already received and processed the promised response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Regardless of whether a push stream has been opened, a server SHOULD send a CANCEL_PUSH frame when it determines that promise will not be fulfilled.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Sending a CANCEL_PUSH frame has no direct effect on the state of existing push streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A client SHOULD NOT send a CANCEL_PUSH frame when it has already received a corresponding push stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A push stream could arrive after a client has sent a CANCEL_PUSH frame, because a server might not have processed the CANCEL_PUSH.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A CANCEL_PUSH frame is sent on the control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The CANCEL_PUSH frame carries a push ID encoded as a variable-length integer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The Push ID field identifies the server push that is being cancelled; see Section 4.6.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the client receives a CANCEL_PUSH frame, that frame might identify a push ID that has not yet been mentioned by a PUSH_PROMISE frame due to reordering.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The SETTINGS frame (type=0x04) conveys configuration parameters that affect how endpoints communicate, such as preferences and constraints on peer behavior.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] SETTINGS frames always apply to an entire HTTP/3 connection, never a single stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A SETTINGS frame MUST be sent as the first frame of each control stream (see Section 6.2.1) by each peer, and it MUST NOT be sent subsequently.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] SETTINGS frames MUST NOT be sent on any stream other than the control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] SETTINGS parameters are not negotiated; they describe characteristics of the sending peer that can be used by the receiving peer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] However, a negotiation can be implied by the use of SETTINGS: each peer uses SETTINGS to advertise a set of supported values.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The definition of the setting would describe how each peer combines the two sets to conclude which choice will be used.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Different values for the same parameter can be advertised by each peer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The same setting identifier MUST NOT occur more than once in the SETTINGS frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The payload of a SETTINGS frame consists of zero or more parameters.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Setting identifiers of the format `0x1f * N + 0x21` for non-negative integer values of `N` are reserved to exercise the requirement that unknown identifiers be ignored.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Endpoints SHOULD include at least one such setting in their SETTINGS frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Setting identifiers that were defined in [HTTP/2] where there is no corresponding HTTP/3 setting have also been reserved (Section 11.2.2).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Each endpoint SHOULD use these initial values to send messages before the peer's SETTINGS frame has arrived, as packets carrying the settings can be lost or delayed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This removes the need to wait for the SETTINGS frame before sending messages.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] For clients using a 1-RTT QUIC connection, the initial value of each server setting is the default value.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] 1-RTT keys will always become available prior to the packet containing SETTINGS being processed by QUIC, even if the server sends SETTINGS immediately.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When a 0-RTT QUIC connection is being used, the initial value of each server setting is the value used in the previous session.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Clients SHOULD store the settings the server provided in the HTTP/3 connection where resumption information was provided, but they MAY opt not to store settings in certain cases (e.g., if the session ticket is received before the SETTINGS frame).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A client MUST comply with stored settings -- or default values if no values are stored -- when attempting 0-RTT.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server can remember the settings that it advertised or store an integrity-protected copy of the values in the ticket and recover the information when accepting 0-RTT data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server uses the HTTP/3 settings values in determining whether to accept 0-RTT data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If the server cannot determine that the settings remembered by a client are compatible with its current settings, it MUST NOT accept 0-RTT data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server MAY accept 0-RTT and subsequently provide different settings in its SETTINGS frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If 0-RTT data is accepted by the server, its SETTINGS frame MUST NOT reduce any limits or alter any values that might be violated by the client with its 0-RTT data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The server MUST include all settings that differ from their default values.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If a server accepts 0-RTT but then sends settings that are not compatible with the previously specified settings, this MUST be treated as a connection error of type H3_SETTINGS_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A variable-length integer that identifies the server push operation.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] QPACK-encoded request header fields for the promised response.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server MUST NOT use a push ID that is larger than the client has provided in a MAX_PUSH_ID frame (Section 7.2.7).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server MAY use the same push ID in multiple PUSH_PROMISE frames.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If so, the decompressed request header sets MUST contain the same fields in the same order, and both the name and the value in each field MUST be exact matches.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Clients SHOULD compare the request header sections for resources promised multiple times.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If a client receives a push ID that has already been promised and detects a mismatch, it MUST respond with a connection error of type H3_GENERAL_PROTOCOL_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Allowing duplicate references to the same push ID is primarily to reduce duplication caused by concurrent requests.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server SHOULD avoid reusing a push ID over a long period.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Clients are likely to consume server push responses and not retain them for reuse over time.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A client MUST NOT send a PUSH_PROMISE frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The GOAWAY frame (type=0x07) is used to initiate graceful shutdown of an HTTP/3 connection by either endpoint.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] GOAWAY allows an endpoint to stop accepting new requests or pushes while still finishing processing of previously received requests and pushes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This enables administrative actions, like server maintenance.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The GOAWAY frame is always sent on the control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] In the server-to-client direction, it carries a QUIC stream ID for a client-initiated bidirectional stream encoded as a variable-length integer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The GOAWAY frame applies to the entire connection, not a specific stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The MAX_PUSH_ID frame (type=0x0d) is used by clients to control the number of server pushes that the server can initiate.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This sets the maximum value for a push ID that the server can use in PUSH_PROMISE and CANCEL_PUSH frames.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The MAX_PUSH_ID frame is always sent on the control stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] A server MUST NOT send a MAX_PUSH_ID frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The maximum push ID is unset when an HTTP/3 connection is created, meaning that a server cannot push until it receives a MAX_PUSH_ID frame.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The MAX_PUSH_ID frame carries a single variable-length integer that identifies the maximum value for a push ID that the server can use; see Section 4.6.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Frame types of the format `0x1f * N + 0x21` for non-negative integer values of `N` are reserved to exercise the requirement that unknown types be ignored (Section 9).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] These frames have no semantics, and they MAY be sent on any stream where frames are allowed to be sent.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This enables their use for application-layer padding.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Frame types that were used in HTTP/2 where there is no corresponding HTTP/3 frame have also been reserved (Section 11.2.1).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] When a stream cannot be completed successfully, QUIC allows the application to abruptly terminate (reset) that stream and communicate a reason; see Section 2.4 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This is referred to as a "stream error".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] An HTTP/3 implementation can decide to close a QUIC stream and communicate the type of error.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Wire encodings of error codes are defined in Section 8.1.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Stream errors are distinct from HTTP status codes that indicate error conditions.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If an entire connection needs to be terminated, QUIC similarly provides mechanisms to communicate a reason; see Section 5.3 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This is referred to as a "connection error".
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Although the reasons for closing streams and connections are called "errors", these actions do not necessarily indicate a problem with the connection or either implementation.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] An endpoint MAY choose to treat a stream error as a connection error under certain circumstances, closing the entire connection in response to a condition on a single stream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Because new error codes can be defined without negotiation (see Section 9), use of an error code in an unexpected context or receipt of an unknown error code MUST be treated as equivalent to H3_NO_ERROR.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] The requested operation cannot be served over HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Error codes of the format `0x1f * N + 0x21` for non-negative integer values of `N` are reserved to exercise the requirement that unknown error codes be treated as equivalent to H3_NO_ERROR (Section 9).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] HTTP/3 permits extension of the protocol.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Within the limitations described in this section, protocol extensions can be used to provide additional services or alter any aspect of the protocol.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This applies to the protocol elements defined in this document.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Extensions are permitted to use new frame types (Section 7.2), new settings (Section 7.2.4.1), new error codes (Section 8), or new unidirectional stream types (Section 6.2).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Implementations MUST ignore unknown or unsupported values in all extensible protocol elements.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Implementations MUST discard data or abort reading on unidirectional streams that have unknown or unsupported types.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This means that any of these extension points can be safely used by extensions without prior arrangement or negotiation.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Extensions that could change the semantics of existing protocol components MUST be negotiated before being used.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] For example, an extension that changes the layout of the HEADERS frame cannot be used until the peer has given a positive signal that this is acceptable.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] Coordinating when such a revised layout comes into effect could prove complex.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] This document does not mandate a specific method for negotiating the use of an extension, but it notes that a setting (Section 7.2.4.1) could be used for that purpose.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p02] If both peers set a value that indicates willingness to use the extension, then the extension can be used.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The security considerations of HTTP/3 should be comparable to those of HTTP/2 with TLS.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3 relies on the HTTP definition of authority.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The use of ALPN in the TLS and QUIC handshakes establishes the target application protocol before application-layer bytes are processed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This does not guarantee protection from all cross-protocol attacks.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The HTTP/3 field encoding allows the expression of names that are not valid field names in the syntax used by HTTP (Section 5.1 of [HTTP]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Requests or responses containing invalid field names MUST be treated as malformed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Similarly, HTTP/3 can transport field values that are not valid.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] While most values that can be encoded will not alter field parsing, carriage return (ASCII 0x0d), line feed (ASCII 0x0a), and the null character (ASCII 0x00) might be exploited by an attacker if they are translated verbatim.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Any request or response that contains a character not permitted in a field value MUST be treated as malformed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Caching responses that are pushed is possible based on the guidance provided by the origin server in the Cache-Control header field.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] However, this can cause issues if a single server hosts more than one tenant.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Where multiple tenants share space on the same server, that server MUST ensure that tenants are not able to push representations of resources that they do not have authority over.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An HTTP/3 connection can demand a greater commitment of resources to operate than an HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2 connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The use of field compression and flow control depend on a commitment of resources for storing a greater amount of state.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The number of PUSH_PROMISE frames is constrained in a similar fashion.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The ability to send undefined protocol elements that the peer is required to ignore can be abused to cause a peer to expend additional processing time.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This might be done by setting multiple undefined SETTINGS parameters, unknown frame types, or unknown stream types.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] All these features -- i.e., server push, unknown protocol elements, field compression -- have legitimate uses.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An endpoint that does not monitor such behavior exposes itself to a risk of denial-of-service attack.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Implementations SHOULD track the use of these features and set limits on their use.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] A large field section (Section 4.1) can cause an implementation to commit a large amount of state.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Header fields that are critical for routing can appear toward the end of a header section, which prevents streaming of the header section to its ultimate destination.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This ordering and other reasons, such as ensuring cache correctness, mean that an endpoint likely needs to buffer the entire header section.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An endpoint can use the SETTINGS_MAX_FIELD_SECTION_SIZE (Section 4.2.2) setting to advise peers of limits that might apply on the size of field sections.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This setting is only advisory, so endpoints MAY choose to send field sections that exceed this limit and risk having the request or response being treated as malformed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This setting is specific to an HTTP/3 connection, so any request or response could encounter a hop with a lower, unknown limit.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] A server that receives a larger field section than it is willing to handle can send an HTTP 431 (Request Header Fields Too Large) status code ([RFC6585]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The CONNECT method can be used to create disproportionate load on a proxy, since stream creation is relatively inexpensive when compared to the creation and maintenance of a TCP connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] A proxy might also maintain some resources for a TCP connection beyond the closing of the stream that carries the CONNECT request, since the outgoing TCP connection remains in the TIME_WAIT state.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Compression can allow an attacker to recover secret data when it is compressed in the same context as data under attacker control.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] There are demonstrable attacks on compression that exploit the characteristics of the web (e.g., [BREACH]).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Implementations communicating on a secure channel MUST NOT compress content that includes both confidential and attacker-controlled data unless separate compression contexts are used for each source of data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Where HTTP/2 employs PADDING frames and Padding fields in other frames to make a connection more resistant to traffic analysis, HTTP/3 can either rely on transport-layer padding or employ the reserved frame and stream types discussed in Sections 7.2.8 and 6.2.3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Reserved stream types can be used to give the appearance of sending traffic even when the connection is idle.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Because HTTP traffic often occurs in bursts, apparent traffic can be used to obscure the timing or duration of such bursts, even to the point of appearing to send a constant stream of data.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Use of padding can result in less protection than might seem immediately obvious.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Redundant padding could even be counterproductive.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] At best, padding only makes it more difficult for an attacker to infer length information by increasing the number of frames an attacker has to observe.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Incorrectly implemented padding schemes can be easily defeated.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Several protocol elements contain nested length elements, typically in the form of frames with an explicit length containing variable-length integers.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This could pose a security risk to an incautious implementer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The use of 0-RTT with HTTP/3 creates an exposure to replay attack.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The anti-replay mitigations in [HTTP-REPLAY] MUST be applied when using HTTP/3 with 0-RTT.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Certain HTTP implementations use the client address for logging or access-control purposes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Several characteristics of HTTP/3 provide an observer an opportunity to correlate actions of a single client or server over time.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3's preference for using a single QUIC connection allows correlation of a user's activity on a site.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] New registries created in this document operate under the QUIC registration policy documented in Section 22.1 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] These registries all include the common set of fields listed in Section 22.1.1 of [QUIC-TRANSPORT].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This document establishes a registry for HTTP/3 frame type codes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The "HTTP/3 Frame Types" registry governs a 62-bit space.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This registry follows the QUIC registry policy; see Section 11.2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] While this registry is separate from the "HTTP/2 Frame Type" registry defined in [HTTP/2], it is preferable that the assignments parallel each other where the code spaces overlap.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] If an entry is present in only one registry, every effort SHOULD be made to avoid assigning the corresponding value to an unrelated operation.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This document establishes a registry for HTTP/3 settings.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The "HTTP/3 Settings" registry governs a 62-bit space.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] While this registry is separate from the "HTTP/2 Settings" registry defined in [HTTP/2], it is preferable that the assignments parallel each other.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The value of the setting unless otherwise indicated.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This document establishes a registry for HTTP/3 error codes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The "HTTP/3 Error Codes" registry manages a 62-bit space.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Registrations for error codes are required to include a description of the error code.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An expert reviewer is advised to examine new registrations for possible duplication with existing error codes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Use of existing registrations is to be encouraged, but not mandated.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In addition to common fields as described in Section 11.2, this registry includes two additional fields.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The entries in Table 4 are registered by this document.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This document establishes a registry for HTTP/3 unidirectional stream types.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The "HTTP/3 Stream Types" registry governs a 62-bit space.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Which endpoint on an HTTP/3 connection may initiate a stream of this type.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3 is strongly informed by HTTP/2, and it bears many similarities.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3 begins from the premise that similarity to HTTP/2 is preferable, but not a hard requirement.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3 departs from HTTP/2 where QUIC differs from TCP, either to take advantage of QUIC features (like streams) or to accommodate important shortcomings (such as a lack of total ordering).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/3 permits use of a larger number of streams (262-1) than HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In contrast to HTTP/2, stream concurrency in HTTP/3 is managed by QUIC.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QUIC considers a stream closed when all data has been received and sent data has been acknowledged by the peer.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/2 considers a stream closed when the frame containing the END_STREAM bit has been committed to the transport.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] As a result, the stream for an equivalent exchange could remain "active" for a longer period of time.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In HTTP/2, only request and response bodies (the frame payload of DATA frames) are subject to flow control.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Due to the presence of other unidirectional stream types, HTTP/3 does not rely exclusively on the number of concurrent unidirectional streams to control the number of concurrent in-flight pushes.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Many framing concepts from HTTP/2 can be elided on QUIC, because the transport deals with them.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Because frames are already on a stream, they can omit the stream number.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Because frames do not block multiplexing (QUIC's multiplexing occurs below this layer), the support for variable-maximum-length packets can be removed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Because stream termination is handled by QUIC, an END_STREAM flag is not required.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Frame payloads are largely drawn from [HTTP/2].
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] However, QUIC includes many features (e.g., flow control) that are also present in HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In these cases, the HTTP mapping does not re-implement them.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] As a result, several HTTP/2 frame types are not required in HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Where an HTTP/2-defined frame is no longer used, the frame ID has been reserved in order to maximize portability between HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 implementations.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Many of the differences arise from the fact that HTTP/2 provides an absolute ordering between frames across all streams, while QUIC provides this guarantee on each stream only.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/2 specifies priority assignments in PRIORITY frames and (optionally) in HEADERS frames.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HPACK was designed with the assumption of in-order delivery.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] A sequence of encoded field sections must arrive (and be decoded) at an endpoint in the same order in which they were encoded.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Because this total ordering is not provided by QUIC, HTTP/3 uses a modified version of HPACK, called QPACK.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QPACK uses a single unidirectional stream to make all modifications to the dynamic table, ensuring a total order of updates.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] HTTP/2 specifies a stream flow-control mechanism.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Although all HTTP/2 frames are delivered on streams, only the DATA frame payload is subject to flow control.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QUIC provides flow control for stream data and all HTTP/3 frame types defined in this document are sent on streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Frame type definitions in HTTP/3 often use the QUIC variable-length integer encoding.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In particular, stream IDs use this encoding, which allows for a larger range of possible values than the encoding used in HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Some frames in HTTP/3 use an identifier other than a stream ID (e.g., push IDs).
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Other than these issues, frame type HTTP/2 extensions are typically portable to QUIC simply by replacing stream 0 in HTTP/2 with a control stream in HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Padding is not defined in HTTP/3 frames.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The PRIORITY region of HEADERS is not defined in HTTP/3 frames.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] RST_STREAM frames do not exist in HTTP/3, since QUIC provides stream lifecycle management.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] SETTINGS frames are sent only at the beginning of the connection.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The PUSH_PROMISE frame does not reference a stream; instead, the push stream references the PUSH_PROMISE frame using a push ID.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In the client-to-server direction, it carries a push ID instead of a server-initiated stream ID.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Frame types defined by extensions to HTTP/2 need to be separately registered for HTTP/3 if still applicable.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The IDs of frames defined in [HTTP/2] have been reserved for simplicity.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Note that the frame type space in HTTP/3 is substantially larger (62 bits versus 8 bits), so many HTTP/3 frame types have no equivalent HTTP/2 code points.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An important difference from HTTP/2 is that settings are sent once, as the first frame of the control stream, and thereafter cannot change.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Some transport-level options that HTTP/2 specifies via the SETTINGS frame are superseded by QUIC transport parameters in HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The HTTP-level setting that is retained in HTTP/3 has the same value as in HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The superseded settings are reserved, and their receipt is an error.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This is removed in favor of the MAX_PUSH_ID frame, which provides a more granular control over server push.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QUIC controls the largest open stream ID as part of its flow-control logic.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QUIC requires both stream and connection flow-control window sizes to be specified in the initial transport handshake.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This setting has no equivalent in HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] In HTTP/3, setting values are variable-length integers (6, 14, 30, or 62 bits long) rather than fixed-length 32-bit fields as in HTTP/2.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This will often produce a shorter encoding, but can produce a longer encoding for settings that use the full 32-bit space.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Settings need to be defined separately for HTTP/2 and HTTP/3.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The IDs of settings defined in [HTTP/2] have been reserved for simplicity.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Note that the settings identifier space in HTTP/3 is substantially larger (62 bits versus 16 bits), so many HTTP/3 settings have no equivalent HTTP/2 code point.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] As QUIC streams might arrive out of order, endpoints are advised not to wait for the peers' settings to arrive before responding to other streams.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] QUIC has the same concepts of "stream" and "connection" errors that HTTP/2 provides.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] This is mapped to H3_GENERAL_PROTOCOL_ERROR except in cases where more specific error codes have been defined.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] H3_REQUEST_REJECTED (in Section 8.1) is used to indicate that a request was not processed.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Error codes need to be defined for HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 separately.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] An intermediary that converts between HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 may encounter error conditions from either upstream.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] There are some rare cases where it is beneficial to propagate the error by mapping it to the closest matching error type to the receiver.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] For example, an intermediary that receives an HTTP/2 stream error of type REFUSED_STREAM from the origin has a clear signal that the request was not processed and that the request is safe to retry.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Propagating this error condition to the client as an HTTP/3 stream error of type H3_REQUEST_REJECTED allows the client to take the action it deems most appropriate.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] Conversion between errors is described in the logical mapping.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The error codes are defined in non-overlapping spaces in order to protect against accidental conversion that could result in the use of inappropriate or unknown error codes for the target version.
[src:http3-protocol/rfc9114-p03] The IETF QUIC Working Group received an enormous amount of support from many people.
